<br>
It's been my experience that people who are Pro-Life, base their decision on their personal spiritual and emotional beliefs.  That means, in their hearts, they believe that abortion is a crime against humanity, or God, and there's no amount of scientific fact that will get them to change their feelings.<br>
<br>
Here's an example of what I'm talking about:<br>
<br>
One of my cousins is married to a very religious Christian woman...I'll call her Annie.  Annie is SO certain that the bible is literal...she actually told me that dinosaur fossils were planted by God as a test of our faith in Him.  In Annie's eyes, there is no mention of dinosaurs in the biblical account of creation, therefore, there WERE no dinosaurs...even though there's an abundance of scientific evidence that points to the contrary.<br>
<br>
Likewise, when Pro-Choicers make their arguments about the lack of cognitive abilities of the embryo/fetus below a certain stage of pregnancy...that means nothing to anti-abortionists.  The Pro-Lifers who base their choice on spiritual beliefs, make the assertion that the soul is still there, regardless of the embryo/fetus's level of neural development.  Other Pro-Lifers that aren't necessarily religious, feel that it's wrong, simply because it's human, and it's a &quot;baby&quot; in their eyes.<br>
<br>
In short, it's an argument that really can't be debated with much of hope of meeting a common ground.  U.S. policies will continue to sway back and forth, depending on the beliefs of the officials in power.  Pro-Choice and Pro-Life activists will lobby for policies that will help their particular cause, and there will be wins and losses for both sides, in terms of government policy on the issue.  <br>
<br>
The one thing that won't change, however, is that people will probably never see eye to eye on the ethics of abortion, and I don't use the word &quot;never&quot; very often.<br>
<br>
Jonqual Fumblethumbs<br>
54 Rake<br>
<br>
Mogron Hammerhand<br>
